<TITLE> Bangladesh visa scam: top KL official in dock </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 20 (bdnews24.com)  A former Malaysian immigration chief has been charged with taking bribes to expedite the approval of entry visas for 4,337 Bangladeshis, a Malaysian online newspaper reported Wednesday. Foreign adviser Iftekhar Ahmed Chowdhury, asked by bdnews24.com for a comment, said he had heard of the case through media reports but had no official information. Foreign secretary Md Touhid Hossain told bdnews24.com that the Malaysian government had not sought any cooperation from Bangladesh in investigating the case. "It is a matter for the Malaysian courts. We have nothing to do with it," Touhid said. Datuk Wahid Md Don, former Immigration Department director general, is accused of receiving bribes of RM 60,000 from businessman Datuk Low Chang Hian as part of the payment for the approval of entry visas for the Bangladeshis, Malaysia's Star Online said. Wahid, who pleaded innocent to a Malaysian court Wednesday, was accused of committing the offence while he was still holding the top post in the department. The senior officer, who was transferred to the Public Service Department pending investigation, was arrested on July 10 and may face up to 20 years in jail if convicted, the newpaper said. bdnews24.
